The [Warsaw Pact](/Warsaw_Pact) (WP), formally christened the Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and Mutual Assistance (TFCMA), was an alliance born of necessity, or perhaps more accurately, of perceived threat and entrenched ideology. Signed in [Warsaw](/Warsaw), [Poland](/Polish_People%27s_Republic), in May 1955, this collective defense treaty brought together the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) and seven other [Eastern Bloc](/Eastern_Bloc) [socialist republics](/List_of_non-communist_socialist_states) across [Central and Eastern Europe](/Central_and_Eastern_Europe). It emerged squarely in the midst of the [Cold War](/Cold_War), a direct military counterpoint to the burgeoning [North Atlantic Treaty Organization](/NATO) (NATO) and the broader [Western Bloc](/Western_Bloc). The nomenclature "Warsaw Pact" generally refers to both the foundational treaty and the resulting [military alliance](/Military_alliance), known variously as the Warsaw Pact Organisation ([WPO](/Warsaw_Pact)) or the Warsaw Treaty Organization ([WTO](/Warsaw_Pact)). It wasn't just a military arrangement; it was the armed arm of the [Council for Mutual Economic Assistance](/Comecon) (Comecon), integrating the Eastern Bloc states economically as well as militarily.

Not to be confused with [Warsaw Convention](/Warsaw_Convention) or [Treaty of Warsaw](/Treaty_of_Warsaw_(disambiguation)).
For other uses, see [Treaty of friendship](/Treaty_of_friendship).

