### Post–Warsaw Pact

[[File:NATO Expansion.gif|thumb|Expansion of [NATO](/NATO) before and after the collapse of communism throughout Central and Eastern Europe]]

The dissolution of the [Warsaw Pact](/Warsaw_Pact) in 1991 didn't signal the end of military alliances in [Europe](/Europe); rather, it marked a dramatic realignment of allegiances that would have been unthinkable just a few years prior. The geopolitical vacuum left by the collapse of the Soviet sphere was quickly filled, often by the very organization the [Warsaw Pact](/Warsaw_Pact) was created to oppose: [NATO](/NATO). On 12 March 1999, the [Czech Republic](/Czech_Republic), [Hungary](/Hungary), and [Poland](/Poland) formally joined [NATO](/NATO), followed in March 2004 by [Bulgaria](/Bulgaria), [Estonia](/Estonia), [Latvia](/Latvia), [Lithuania](/Lithuania), [Romania](/Romania), [Slovenia](/Slovenia), and [Slovakia](/Slovakia). [Croatia](/Croatia) and [Albania](/Albania) completed this eastward expansion on 1 April 2009. The irony of former adversaries embracing their erstwhile opponent was not lost on keen observers, a testament to the fluid, self-serving nature of international relations.

Meanwhile, the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union)'s primary successor state, [Russia](/Russia), along with several other post-Soviet states, sought to establish new security frameworks. They formed the [Collective Security Treaty Organization](/Collective_Security_Treaty_Organization) (CSTO) in 1992, an attempt to maintain a degree of military cooperation and influence within the former Soviet space. Concurrently, the "Shanghai Five," established in 1996, evolved into the [Shanghai Cooperation Organisation](/Shanghai_Cooperation_Organisation) (SCO) with the addition of [Uzbekistan](/Uzbekistan) in 2001, focusing on regional security and economic cooperation in [Central Asia](/Central_Asia).

A chilling postscript to the [Cold War](/Cold_War) era emerged in November 2005, when the Polish government opened its [Warsaw Treaty](/Warsaw_Pact) archives to the [Institute of National Remembrance](/Institute_of_National_Remembrance). In January 2006, some 1,300 declassified documents were published, though the Polish government initially reserved 100 documents for further military declassification. Eventually, 30 of these were released, but 70 remained stubbornly secret. Among the most explosive revelations was the [Warsaw Treaty](/Warsaw_Pact)'s nuclear war plan, infamously codenamed "[Seven Days to the River Rhine](/Seven_Days_to_the_River_Rhine)." This document detailed a rapid, swift invasion and capture of [Austria](/Austria), [Denmark](/Denmark), [Germany](/Germany), and the [Netherlands](/Netherlands) east of the [Rhine](/Rhine), explicitly envisioning the use of [nuclear weapons](/Nuclear_weapon) following a hypothetical [NATO](/NATO) first strike. The declassification offered a terrifying glimpse into the detailed, destructive planning that underpinned the decades of nuclear standoff, a stark reminder of how close the world teetered on the brink.

